Load packages

library("plyr")
library("ggplot2")
library("reshape2")

Read data

# read file
setwd("/Users/hfresq/github/data-viz/ebola")
health1 <- read.csv("Microbe-scope-bugs.csv")

Clean up the file

# first row is additional documentation, not real data. drop it.
# columns after 27 are source documentation. drop them.
health2 <- health1[2:nrow(health1),1:27]
health3 <- rename(health2, c("X"="bug", 
                              "yearly.fatalities"="yearly.fatalities.W.round",
                              "X.2"="yearly.fatalities.W.raw",
                              "X.3"="note.2",
                              "yearly.fatalities.1"="yearly.fatalities.US.round",                                                        
                              "yearly.fatalities.2"="yearly.fatalities.AF.round",                                                         
                              "yearly.fatalities.3"="yearly.fatalities.AF.raw",
                              "X.4"="note.3",
                              "X.5"="note.4",
                              "note.2"="note.5"))
health3[,"X.1"] <- NULL



# clean up some variables we want to plot


# A. disease name
# Split into two columns - main name and details. 
# I've done this in a very hackish way! I need practice with regular expressions.
health3$bug2 <- chartr(old="(", new="7", as.character(health3$bug))

bnames <- colsplit(health3$bug2, "7", names=c("bug2a","bug2b"))
bnames$bug2b <- gsub(')','', bnames$bug2b)

health3 <- cbind(health3, bnames)

trim <- function (x) gsub("^\\s+|\\s+$", "", x)
health3$bug2a <- trim(health3$bug2a)
health3$bug2b <- trim(health3$bug2b)

# further refinements to disease labels to match graph
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Bird Flu"),"bug2a"] <- "Avian Flu"
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Bird Flu"),"bug2b"] <- "(H5N1)"
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Bubonic Plague"),"bug2b"] <- ""
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Malaria"),"bug2b"] <- ""
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Pertussis"),"bug2a"] <- "Whooping Cough"
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Whooping Cough"),"bug2b"] <- ""
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Syphilis"),"bug2b"] <- ""
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Tuberculosis"),"bug2b"] <- ""
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Norovirus"),"bug2b"] <- '"vomiting bug"'
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Rotavirus"),"bug2b"] <- '"stomach bug"'
health3[which(health3$bug2a == "Rhinovirus"),"bug2b"] <- "common cold"

# Use this to check data manipulations
# health3[,c("bug", "bug2a", "bug2b")]



# B. Case Fatality
health3$CFR2 <- as.numeric(gsub('%','',health3$case.fatality.rate))

# This isn't plotted linearly. Transform raw data.
health3$CFR3 <- ifelse(health3$CFR2 < 0.1,
                       health3$CFR2 * 100,
                          ifelse(health3$CFR2 < 1,
                          health3$CFR2 * (10/0.9) + 8.888,
                          health3$CFR2 + 20))

# move this point up slightly so it doesn't overlap with another of the same values.
health3[which(health3$bug2a=="Avian Flu"), "CFR3"] <- health3[which(health3$bug2a=="Avian Flu"), "CFR3"] + 2

# Use this to check data manipulations
# health3[order(health3$CFR2), c("case.fatality.rate", "CFR2", "CFR3", "bug2a", "bug2b")]



# B. Reproductive Rate
health3$ABRR2 <- as.numeric(levels(health3$average.basic.reproductive.rate)[health3$average.basic.reproductive.rate])
# Use this to check data manipulations
# health3[, c("ABRR2", "average.basic.reproductive.rate")]


# C. Mode of Transmission
# table(health3$primary.mode.of.transmission, useNA="always")
health3$PMT2 <- health3$primary.mode.of.transmission
# replace blanks with NAs
health3[health3$primary.mode.of.transmission == "", "PMT2"] <- NA
# collapse airborne and airborne droplet into one category
health3[health3$primary.mode.of.transmission == "airborne droplet", "PMT2"] <- "airborne"
# the published graph characterizes cholera as airborne.
health3[health3$bug == "Cholera", "PMT2"] <- "airborne"

# Use this to check data manipulations
# health3[, c("PMT2", "primary.mode.of.transmission")]

Finalize dataset

health4 <- subset(health3, 
                  !(bug %in% c("Anthrax (untreated)", "Malaria (P. falciparum)")), 
                  c("bug2a", "bug2b", "ABRR2", "CFR2", "CFR3", "PMT2"))

Plot!

#define y-axis breaks
yax <- c(0, 0.1, 1, seq(10, 100, 10))

g1 <- ggplot(data=health4, 
            aes(x=ABRR2,
            y=CFR3, 
            color=PMT2)) +
      geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=40, ymax=70), fill="gray95", colour=NA, alpha=0.5) +
      geom_ribbon(aes(ymin= 0, ymax=20), fill="gray95", colour=NA, alpha=0.5) +
      geom_point(shape=16, size=6) + 
      geom_text(aes(label=paste(" ", bug2a)), hjust=0, vjust=0.5, show_guide=FALSE) +
      labs(x="CONTAGIOUSNESS (average basic reproduction number (R0), no. of people one perosn will likely infect)",
           y="DEADLINESS (case fatality rate)",
           title="The Microbe-scope") +
      scale_colour_manual(name="PRIMARY TRANSIMISSION METHOD",
                          values=c("cadetblue4", "lightgoldenrod4", "deeppink", "gray40", "darkslategray2", "darkgoldenrod1", "gray80")) +
      scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 120, 10), minor_breaks = NULL, label=function(x){return(paste(yax, "%"))}) + 
      scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 17.9, 1), minor_breaks = NULL) + 
      geom_hline(aes(yintercept=20)) + 
      geom_vline(aes(xintercept=1)) + 
      theme(plot.title = element_text(size=20, face="bold", hjust=0, vjust=1),
            axis.title.x = element_text(color="gray"),
            axis.title.y = element_text(color="gray"),
            legend.title = element_text(colour="gray"),
            legend.key = element_rect(fill=NA),
            legend.position = "top",
            panel.background = element_rect(fill = NA),
            panel.grid.major = element_line(linetype = "dotted", colour = "gray"),
            panel.border = element_rect(linetype = "dotted", colour = "gray", fill=NA)
            ) 
g1

Additional modifications I would like to make

There are a few things I couldnt figure out

  • More control over the axis labels, e.g.choosing line breaks.
  • Adding annotation to the axies, e.g. R0=1, disease not likely to spread
  • Controling the ranges shown. My plot extents past zero on both axies, even though I set the limits to zero!
  • Positioning data labels for better readability.
